### The Key Takeaway: Most Cross-Shoppers Are Confused, Not Miscategorized

**Only 13 users (7.3% of business-email holders, ~1.1% of the full cohort) are from clearly enterprise/corporate organizations** — the kind of users who should definitively be on a Business plan. The rest fall into a gray area:

The **churches, nonprofits, and small media companies** (71 users combined) are the most interesting group. These organizations likely *do* need multi-seat licensing or broader coverage, but they may not self-identify as "Business" — they're small teams that feel more like individuals. The persona card labels probably don't speak to them. A church media director or a 3-person production house might click "Individual" first, realize it doesn't fit, then explore "Business" to compare.

The **freelancers with personal brand domains** (16 users) are almost certainly Individual plan customers who are just curious about business pricing — they're correctly starting on Individual but peeking at Business to make sure they're not missing something.

The **289 free-email users** (Gmail, Yahoo, etc.) are the biggest group with any identity signal, and they skew heavily personal — 237 of them are Gmail. These are most likely individual creators who clicked "Business" out of curiosity or uncertainty, not because they need enterprise licensing.

**Bottom line:** The cross-shopping behavior appears to be driven more by **unclear card descriptions** than by users genuinely belonging on the wrong plan. The ambiguous middle — churches, nonprofits, small production studios — is where clearer messaging about "who this is for" would help the most. Something like "Teams of 2+" or "Need licenses for employees?" on the Business card could reduce the confusion without requiring these users to click through and compare.

