## Distinguishing Behaviors for Converters vs Non-Converters who visit the Pricing Page

## 1. Repeat Pricing Visits Are the Strongest Conversion Signal

This is the single most predictive behavior in the data:

| Pricing Page Views | Users | Subscription Conv. Rate |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 view only | ~10,590 | ~1.8% (est.) |
| 2+ views | 4,668 (30.6%) | **5.0%** |
| 3+ views | 878 (5.8%) | **14.6%** |

Users who come back to pricing 3+ times within 7 days convert at **5x the overall rate**. This tells you converters are comparison-shopping — they look at pricing, go browse content, come back to pricing, browse more, and return again before committing. The average time between pricing views is ~4.5 hours for the 2nd visit and ~10 hours for the 3rd, suggesting these are spread across multiple sessions over days, not a single session.

Non-converters overwhelmingly view pricing once and never return.

---

## 2. Converters Engage with Content Before (and Between) Pricing Visits

Among pricing visitors who played at least one song within 7 days, **5.0% subscribed** — nearly 2x the overall rate. But the pattern goes deeper when you look at the full journey:

**Pricing → Played Song → Sign-Up Form → Signed Up → Subscribed:**

- 15,258 → 2,714 (17.8%) → 633 (23.3% of players) → 134 (21.2%) → 20 (14.9%)

The key insight: once someone plays a song **and** views the sign-up form, their conversion rate to actually signing up is 21%. And of those who sign up after playing songs, 15% subscribe. Compare that to the overall funnel where only 7.6% ever reach the sign-up form at all.

Song search also correlates — 12.4% of pricing visitors searched for songs, and searchers subscribed at 3.7% (vs. 2.8% overall). Favoriting a song is an even stronger signal: only 2.3% of pricing visitors favorited a song, but those who did subscribed at **6.1%**.

Non-converters overwhelmingly view pricing and leave without ever interacting with the music catalog.

---

## 3. Existing Account Holders (Sign-In Path) Convert at 3x the Rate

Two distinct converter paths emerged:

**New user path** (Pricing → Sign Up → Subscribe): 597 users signed up, 64 subscribed = **10.7% conversion from sign-up to subscription**. Average time from pricing to subscription: ~15 hours.

**Returning user path** (Pricing → Sign In → Subscribe): 578 users signed in, 50 subscribed = **8.7% conversion from sign-in to subscription**. Average time: ~30 hours.

Both paths convert much better than the average (2.8%), but the new user path actually edges out returning users slightly. The bigger story is that **these two groups account for ~114 of the 429 subscriptions** — meaning the remaining ~315 converters were already logged in when they visited pricing (they didn't need to sign in or sign up during the window).

This implies the majority of converters are **existing free account holders** who are already authenticated and browsing the platform regularly.

